The White House has released a presidential proclamation declaring October 6, 2009, as German-American Day. The proclamation recognizes the contributions of German Americans to the development of the United States since the 17th century. It highlights their role in various fields such as farming, entrepreneurship, and patriotism. The proclamation also acknowledges the influence of German culture and traditions in American society, as well as the historical ties between Germany and the United States. The proclamation encourages Americans to learn more about the history of German Americans and commemorate their contributions.